                 Welcome to the Computer Training Web page!

   The training room continues to be very active, with classes for both
   the staff and the general public.  With overhead screen projection and
   hands-on training at individual computers, it is an ideal setting.

   These classes are offered free of charge.  Most of them will be
   hands-on sessions lasting about two hours.  Classes are currently
   limited to ten students and are given several times a month.

   Staff will be kept posted on monthly sessions through library e-mail.
   The general public can find their course offerings listed below:

   Location:    Main Library training room, 3rd floor, Room 318

                        Introduction to the Internet

   Topics:    Internet and the World Wide Web, Web browsers, home pages,
   hypertext, menus and toolbars, bookmarks, and a sampling of many
   popular Web sites.  There will be an interactive slideshow/internet
   presentation followed by hands-on practice.

   Audience:    Anyone with little or no Internet experience

                          Internet Tips and Tricks

   Topics:     33 useful hints for successfully browsing the Internet -
   includes working with multiple windows, scrolling and finding, keyboard
   shortcuts, links and addresses, searching and typing, right mouse
   button choices, advertiser tricks, icon consolidation, text size
   alterations, and more.

   Audience:     Anyone who has taken the Introduction to the Internet
   session, or who is familiar with the Internet and wants further
   training.

                            Websearch Techniques

   Topics:   Search engines, methods of searching, using well-known names,
   simple and complex category search and keyword search, Boolean logic, a
   sampling of several search engines, use of logic operators, and special
   keywords.

   Audience:    Anyone who has taken the Introduction to the Internet
   session, or who is familiar with the Internet and wants further
   training.

                              E-Mail Techniques

   Topics:      Exploring a typical e-mail program, including replies,
   forwards, attachments, signature files, and address books; exploring
   Hotmail, one of the many free e-mail programs; exploring e-mail mailing
   lists for sharing and participating in all manner of personal
   interests, hobbies, etc.

   Audience:     Anyone who has taken the Introduction to the Internet
   session, or who is familiar with the Internet and wants further
   training.

                          Deeper into the Internet

   Topics:     Printing from the Web selected pages, partial pages and
   pictures; changing preferences, such as home page, text only, and
   overriding web colors for printing; creating and filling folders in
   Bookmarks and Favorites; downloading plug-ins and making them
   operational; exploring the  Carolin On-line Catalog on our Website and
   learning how to use it for looking up and/or reserving materials.

   Audience:    Anyone who has taken the Introduction to the Internet
   session, or who is familiar with the Internet and wants further
   training.

                                Registration

